{"altmetric_id":13598165,"counts":{"readers":{"mendeley":4,"citeulike":0,"connotea":0},"total":{"posts_count":10},"twitter":{"unique_users_count":7,"unique_users":["worldjsurg","BVMurciasalud","AntoniodeLacy","MartinCornillet","lapcolo","RMakhoul","bjorkstrom_lab"],"posts_count":8},"facebook":{"unique_users_count":1,"unique_users":["162255510496328"],"posts_count":2}},"selected_quotes":["the adoption of ALPPS cannot be recommended without further data #liver #cancer #prognosis"],"citation":{"abstract":"Liver resection combined with colorectal surgery (CRS) is the only curative option in many patients presenting with synchronous colorectal cancer and liver metastases (CRLM). Simultaneous resection has been shown to offer benefits in patients with low hepatic tumor load; however, in the setting of in situ colorectal tumor with extensive CRLM and a small predicted future liver remnant (FLR), the use of simultaneous ALPPS and CRS is controversial, lacking outcome data.\nThirty-one cases of simultaneous ALPPS and CRS prospectively entered into the International ALPPS Registry were examined. Univariate analysis was used to identify factors associated with 90-day mortality after stage-2.\nThirty patients (97%) completed both stages. CRS was performed during stage-1 in 22 patients (73%). Seven patients (23%) had severe complications (Clavien-Dindo\u00a0\u2265\u00a0IIIb) following stage-2 ALPPS. The 90-day mortality rate was 15%. Patients who had a severe complication after stage-1 were significantly more likely to have 90-day mortality following stage-2 (p\u00a0=\u00a00.002). MELD score\u00a0>\u00a010 on postoperative day-5 after stage-1 was also significantly associated with 90-day mortality (p\u00a0=\u00a00.011). Disease-free survival and overall survival were 36% and 76% at 1\u00a0year, respectively.\nIn light of the high mortality and poor long-term survival identified in this series, the adoption of ALPPS with CRS cannot be recommended without further data. Patients who suffer severe complications or have an elevated MELD score after stage-1 are at higher risk of mortality following stage-2.","altmetric_jid":"4f6fa5163cf058f610003741","authors":["Kerollos Nashat Wanis","Suzana Buac","Michael Linecker","Victoria Ardiles","Mauro Enrique Tun-Abraham","Ricardo Robles-Campos","Massimo Malago","Eduardo de Santiba\u00f1es","Pierre-Alain Clavien","Roberto Hernandez-Alejandro"],"doi":"10.1007\/s00268-016-3818-1","first_seen_on":"2016-11-14T15:35:47+00:00","funders":["niehs"],"isbns":[],"issns":["1432-2323","0364-2313"],"journal":"World Journal of Surgery","last_mentioned_on":1497871521,"links":["http:\/\/link.springer.com\/article\/10.1007%2Fs00268-016-3818-1","http:\/\/www.readcube.com\/articles\/10.1007%2Fs00268-016-3818-1?shared_access_token=H9BcKWE6A1E2lcJYkzOlB_e4RwlQNchNByi7wbcMAY4ZFf9U56Tdqk6Co48E_sdq9WkpNk4Bwa5tPHHgALl0MAhR4YUUnlRZFdf8xddlSeX181bGSVoXXgCU0WDX5VnJG6Yf4Fb_nIXt9-z_e945wseBhVy5bFCCvqGGjtFd9No%3D","http:\/\/link.springer.com\/openurl?genre=article&id=doi:10.1007\/s00268-016-3818-1","https:\/\/link.springer.com\/article\/10.1007\/s00268-016-3818-1?no-access=true","http:\/\/dx.doi.org\/10.1007\/s00268-016-3818-1"],"pdf_url":"http:\/\/link.springer.com\/content\/pdf\/10.1007%2Fs00268-016-3818-1.pdf","pmid":"27837237","pubdate":"2016-11-11T00:00:00+00:00","publisher":"Springer International Publishing","publisher_subjects":[{"name":"Clinical Sciences","scheme":"era"}],"scopus_subjects":["Medicine","Health Sciences"],"subjects":["generalsurgery"],"title":"Patient Survival After Simultaneous ALPPS and Colorectal Resection","type":"article","uri":"http:\/\/link.springer.com\/10.1007\/s00268-016-3818-1","mendeley_url":"http:\/\/www.mendeley.com\/research\/patient-survival-after-simultaneous-alpps-colorectal-resection"},"altmetric_score":{"score":4.7,"score_history":{"1y":4.7,"6m":0.5,"3m":0,"1m":0,"1w":0,"6d":0,"5d":0,"4d":0,"3d":0,"2d":0,"1d":0,"at":4.7},"context_for_score":{"all":{"total_number_of_other_articles":8392157,"me